{"title_page": "9.3\u00d762mm", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{More footnotes|date=October 2008}}\n{{Refimprove|date=November 2009}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox firearm cartridge\n| name = 9.3\u00d762mm\n| image = 9.3x62mm-Norma-Oryx-15g(232gr)-cartridge.png | image_size = 300px\n| caption = The 9.3\u00d762mm [[cartridge (weaponry)|cartridge]].\n| origin = [[German Empire]]\n| type = Rifle\n<!-- Service history -->\n| service = \n| used_by = \n| wars = \n<!-- Production history -->\n| designer = Otto Bock\n| design_date = 1905\n| manufacturer = \n| production_date = 1905\u2013present\n| number = \n| variants = \n<!-- Specifications -->\n| is_SI_specs = yes\n| parent = \n| case_type = Rimless, bottleneck\n| bullet = 9.30\n| neck = 9.92\n| shoulder = 11.45\n| base = 12.10\n| rim_dia = 11.95\n| rim_thick = 1.30\n| case_length = 62.00\n| length = 83.60\n| case_capacity = 5.07\n| rifling = 360 mm (1-14.17 in)\n| primer = Large rifle\n| max_pressure = 390.00\n<!-- Ballistic performance -->\n| is_SI_ballistics = \n| bw1 = 230\n| btype1 = Norma Ecostrike\n| vel1 = 2641\n| en1 = 3563\n| bw2 = 232\n| btype2 = Norma Oryx\n| vel2 = 2625\n| en2 = 3551\n| bw3 = 275\n| btype3 = Norma Solid\n| vel3 = 2450\n| en3 = 3666\n| bw4 = 285\n| btype4 = Norma Oryx\n| vel4 = 2362\n| en4 = 3544\n| bw5 = 286\n| btype5 = Swift A-Frame\n| vel5 = 2362\n| en5 = 3544\n| test_barrel_length = {{convert|610|mm|in}}\n| balsrc = Norma<ref name=\"Norma\">[https://www.norma-ammunition.com/en/Our-Products/ 9.3x62mm data from Norma]</ref>\n}}\n\n[[File:9.3X62-30-06-8X57-6.5X55-308.JPG|thumb|From left to right 9.3\u00d762mm, [[.30-06 Springfield]], [[7.92\u00d757mm Mauser]], [[6.5\u00d755mm]] and [[.308 Winchester]] cartridges.]]\n[[File:Norma-9.3x62-15g(232gr)-Oryx-20pcs.jpg|thumb|Norma Oryx Soft Point cartridges in plastic holder (producer [[Norma Precision]] AB, Sweden)]]\n\nThe '''9.3\u00d762mm''' (also known as '''9.3\u00d762mm Mauser''') is a rimless, bottlenecked rifle cartridge designed in 1905 by German gunmaker Otto Bock. It is suitable for hunting medium to large game animals in [[Africa]], [[Europe]], and [[North America]]. At a typical velocity of 720 m/s (2362 ft/s), its 286 gr (18.5 g) standard load balances [[recoil]] and power for effective use at up to about 250m (275 yds). The [[C.I.P.]] Maximum Average Pressure (MAP) for the 9.3\u00d762mm is {{convert|390.00|MPa|psi|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"GunDigest - 9.3 x 62mm\">{{cite web|title=Greatest Cartridges: 9.3\u00d762 Mauser, Effective on About Everything|url=http://gundigest.com/reloading/greatest-cartridges-9-3x62-mauser-effective-on-about-everything|website=gundigest.com|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe 9.3\u00d762mm was designed to fit into the [[Gewehr 98|Mauser 98]] [[bolt-action]] rifle.<ref name=\"GunDigest - 9.3 x 62mm\" /> European hunters and settlers in Africa often chose military rifles for their reliability and low cost, but colonial governments in Africa fearful of rebellions often banned military-caliber rifles and ammunition. The 9.3\u00d762mm was never a military cartridge and so never had this problem. Like their military counterparts, Mauser rifles chambered in 9.3\u00d762mm were relatively inexpensive and quite reliable. Because of these factors 9.3x62mm quickly became popular and usage of the cartridge became widespread.\n\nThe [[9.3\u00d774mmR]] is a rimmed cartridge that evolved from the 9.3\u00d772mmR [[black powder]] cartridge. The energy levels of the 9.3\u00d762mm and [[9.3\u00d774mmR]] cartridges are similar but the cartridges are unrelated. The rimmed cartridge is slightly longer than the 9.3x62mm, allowing for lower pressure in the case while retaining muzzle velocity and energy.\n\n==Ammunition==\nThe 9.3\u00d762mm was first loaded with a {{convert|18.5|g|gr|}} bullet at a [[muzzle velocity]] of 655&nbsp;m/s (2,150&nbsp;ft/s). After [[World War I]] some companies increased the velocity to around 730&nbsp;m/s (2,400&nbsp;ft/s), and brought out lighter bullets. Rifles set up for the original load must have their sights readjusted to shoot the newer load to point of aim. Adding to the confusion, loads at both velocities are available today. Several European firms load 9.3\u00d762mm ammunition, including [[Nammo|Lapua]], [[Norma (company)|Norma]], [[RUAG|RUAG Ammotech (RWS)]], [[SAKO]], and [[Prvi Partizan|Prvi Partizan (PPU)]] as well as [[Denel|Denel (PMP)]] of [[South Africa]], and it is widely available in [[Africa]].<ref name=\"Biggamehunting - 9.3 x 62mm Mauser\">{{cite web|title=The 9.3x62mm Mauser|url=http://thebiggamehuntingblog.com/2013/09/the-93x62mm-mauser-html/|website=thebiggamehuntingblog.com|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn [[England]], [[Kynoch]] the well-known cartridge manufacturer, produced ammunition, referring to the 9.3\u00d762mm as '9.3mm Mauser'. Typically it was loaded as 'Metal Covered Soft Nose Bullet', {{convert|18.5|g|gr}} with the base marked simply Kynoch 9.3&nbsp;mm. This is no longer listed by them.\n\n==Elsewhere==\n{{More citations needed section|date=March 2020}}\nIn several [[European countries]], the 9.3x62mm remains a popular cartridge for hunting game like moose and wild boar, and it is offered as a standard chambering in rifles from most makers there. The [[CZ-USA]] [[CZ 550]] rifle in 9.3x62mm chambering became available in [[North America]] in 2002, and both rifle and cartridge are gaining a strong following there, as the cartridge has a slight power edge over the popular [[.35 Whelen]] cartridge. In [[US]], several ammunition makers including [[Federal Premium Ammunition|Federal]], [[Hornady]], [[Nosler]], and Swift offer factory-loaded 9.3x62mm sporting ammunition. Since surplus Scandinavian and European Mausers were been brought to Canada in 9.3 calibre in the early 1950s, Canadian hunters have used the 9.3\u00d762mm cartridge to hunt large game in [[Canada]] including [[bison]], all the deer species, and large bears. In recent years, [[\u010cesk\u00e1 Zbrojovka firearms|CZ]] of [[Czech Republic]], as well as [[SAKO]] and Tikka of [[Finland]] have imported many 9.3x62mm rifles to [[Canada]] and [[US]] where demand continues to be high.\n\n==Adequacy==\nThe 9.3\u00d762mm is considered ideal for hunting the larger and tougher African game species, such as [[lion]]s, [[leopard]]s, [[gemsbok]]s, [[Common eland|eland]]s, and [[wildebeest]]s. Most hunters consider it a viable all-around cartridge comparable to [[.338 Winchester Magnum]], [[9.3\u00d764mm Brenneke]], and [[.375 H&H Magnum]]. The 9.3\u00d762mm has taken cleanly every dangerous game species in [[Africa]].  Though it is of smaller bore than the legal minimum .375 calibre for dangerous game in most countries, many countries specifically make an exception for the 9.3\u00d762mm.<ref>[http://www.huntinginafrica.co.za/more-info/minimum-required-caliber/ Minimum required caliber for hunting Africa]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.farrenglobaladventures.com/Caliber%20Minimums.htm |title=Minimum Calibers for Africa |access-date=10 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714021703/http://www.farrenglobaladventures.com/Caliber%20Minimums.htm |archive-date=14 July 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>[http://www.napha-namibia.com/legal-information/hunting-laws-rifle-importation/ Hunting Laws & Rifle Importation NAPHA Namibia Professional Hunting Association]</ref> The 9.3\u00d762mm is considered adequate for European and North American game animals that may become dangerous, such as feral hogs and [[bear]]s. \n\n[[Sambar (deer)|Sambar]] hunters in [[Australia]] are turning to the 9.3\u00d762mm due to Federal Government's 1996 ban on self-loading rifles. {{cn|date=March 2012}} Thousands of deer hunters at once needed bolt-action rifles which delivered one-shot knockdown power on [[Sambar (deer)|Sambar]], and the 9.3\u00d762mm calibre has proven to be well up to that task.\n\n==See also==\n* [[9 mm caliber]]\n* [[9.3\u00d774mmR]]\n* [[9.3\u00d764mm Brenneke]]\n* [[List of rifle cartridges]]\n* [[Table of handgun and rifle cartridges]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{Cite web\n |url=http://www.reloadersnest.com/article_9362_oct2803.asp \n |title=The 9,3 x 62 mm Mauser is making a strong come back! \n |publisher=reloaders \n |accessdate=24 February 2006 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207003649/http://www.reloadersnest.com/article_9362_oct2803.asp \n |archivedate=7 February 2009 \n}}\n* {{Cite web\n |url         = http://www.african-hunter.com/the_9_3_x_62_mauser.htm\n |title       = The 9.3 x 62 Mauser\n |publisher   = African Hunter\n |accessdate  = 24 February 2006\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20051215151816/http://www.african-hunter.com/the_9_3_x_62_mauser.htm\n |archivedate = 15 December 2005\n |url-status     = dead\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\n* {{Cite web\n | url = http://www.realguns.com/archives/152.htm\n | title = \u010cesk\u00e1 Zbrojovka's CZ 550 FS 9.3x62\n | publisher = RGI Media\n | accessdate = 9 April 2008\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.gunsandammomag.com/cs/Satellite/IMO_GA/Story_C/A+Most+Marvelous+Metric?packedargs=pagenum%3D1 A Most Marvelous Metric - The 9.3mm holds the light heavyweight crown among European bore sizes and should be more popular stateside than it is - by Craig Boddington]\n*[http://www.jww.de/445,319/ Jagen Weltweit, Die Partone 9,3x62 by Norbert Klups (German)]\n* 9.3x62 - Otto Bock's Cartridge http://www.africanxmag.com/otto_bock%27s_cartridge.htm\n{{DEFAULTSORT:9.3x62mm}}\n[[Category:Pistol and rifle cartridges]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{More footnotes|date=October 2008}}\n{{Refimprove|date=November 2009}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox firearm cartridge\n| name = 9.3\u00d762mm\n| image = 9.3x62mm-Norma-Oryx-15g(232gr)-cartridge.png | image_size = 300px\n| caption = The 9.3\u00d762mm [[cartridge (weaponry)|cartridge]].\n| origin = [[German Empire]]\n| type = Rifle\n<!-- Service history -->\n| service = \n| used_by = \n| wars = \n<!-- Production history -->\n| designer = Otto Bock\n| design_date = 1905\n| manufacturer = \n| production_date = 1905\u2013present\n| number = \n| variants = \n<!-- Specifications -->\n| is_SI_specs = yes\n| parent = \n| case_type = Rimless, bottleneck\n| bullet = 9.30\n| neck = 9.92\n| shoulder = 11.45\n| base = 12.10\n| rim_dia = 11.95\n| rim_thick = 1.30\n| case_length = 62.00\n| length = 83.60\n| case_capacity = 5.07\n| rifling = 360 mm (1-14.17 in)\n| primer = Large rifle\n| max_pressure = 390.00\n<!-- Ballistic performance -->\n| is_SI_ballistics = \n| bw1 = 230\n| btype1 = Norma Ecostrike\n| vel1 = 2641\n| en1 = 3563\n| bw2 = 232\n| btype2 = Norma Oryx\n| vel2 = 2625\n| en2 = 3551\n| bw3 = 275\n| btype3 = Norma Solid\n| vel3 = 2450\n| en3 = 3666\n| bw4 = 285\n| btype4 = Norma Oryx\n| vel4 = 2362\n| en4 = 3544\n| bw5 = 286\n| btype5 = Swift A-Frame\n| vel5 = 2362\n| en5 = 3544\n| test_barrel_length = {{convert|610|mm|in}}\n| balsrc = Norma<ref name=\"Norma\">[https://www.norma-ammunition.com/en/Our-Products/ 9.3x62mm data from Norma]</ref>\n}}\n\n[[File:9.3X62-30-06-8X57-6.5X55-308.JPG|thumb|From left to right 9.3\u00d762mm, [[.30-06 Springfield]], [[7.92\u00d757mm Mauser]], [[6.5\u00d755mm]] and [[.308 Winchester]] cartridges.]]\n[[File:Norma-9.3x62-15g(232gr)-Oryx-20pcs.jpg|thumb|Norma Oryx Soft Point cartridges in plastic holder (producer [[Norma Precision]] AB, Sweden)]]\n\nThe '''9.3\u00d762mm''' (also known as '''9.3\u00d762mm Mauser''') is a rimless, bottlenecked rifle cartridge designed in 1905 by German gunmaker Otto Bock. It is suitable for hunting medium to large game animals in [[Africa]], [[Europe]], and [[North America]]. At a typical velocity of 720 m/s (2362 ft/s), its 286 gr (18.5 g) standard load balances [[recoil]] and power for effective use at up to about 250m (275 yds). The [[C.I.P.]] Maximum Average Pressure (MAP) for the 9.3\u00d762mm is {{convert|390.00|MPa|psi|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"GunDigest - 9.3 x 62mm\">{{cite web|title=Greatest Cartridges: 9.3\u00d762 Mauser, Effective on About Everything|url=http://gundigest.com/reloading/greatest-cartridges-9-3x62-mauser-effective-on-about-everything|website=gundigest.com|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe 9.3\u00d762mm was designed to fit into the [[Gewehr 98|Mauser 98]] [[bolt-action]] rifle.<ref name=\"GunDigest - 9.3 x 62mm\" /> European hunters and settlers in Africa often chose military rifles for their reliability and low cost, but colonial governments in Africa fearful of rebellions often banned military-caliber rifles and ammunition. The 9.3\u00d762mm was never a military cartridge and so never had this problem. Like their military counterparts, Mauser rifles chambered in 9.3\u00d762mm were relatively inexpensive and quite reliable. Because of these factors 9.3x62mm quickly became popular and usage of the cartridge became widespread.\n\nThe [[9.3\u00d774mmR]] is a rimmed cartridge that evolved from the 9.3\u00d772mmR [[black powder]] cartridge. The energy levels of the 9.3\u00d762mm and [[9.3\u00d774mmR]] cartridges are similar but the cartridges are unrelated. The rimmed cartridge is slightly longer than the 9.3x62mm, allowing for lower pressure in the case while retaining muzzle velocity and energy.\n\n==Ammunition==\nThe 9.3\u00d762mm was first loaded with a {{convert|18.5|g|gr|}} bullet at a [[muzzle velocity]] of 655&nbsp;m/s (2,150&nbsp;ft/s). After [[World War I]] some companies increased the velocity to around 730&nbsp;m/s (2,400&nbsp;ft/s), and brought out lighter bullets. Rifles set up for the original load must have their sights readjusted to shoot the newer load to point of aim. Adding to the confusion, loads at both velocities are available today. Several European firms load 9.3\u00d762mm ammunition, including [[Nammo|Lapua]], [[Norma (company)|Norma]], RWS, [[SAKO]], and PPU (Prvi Partizan) as well as PMP of [[South Africa]], and it is widely available in [[Africa]].<ref name=\"Biggamehunting - 9.3 x 62mm Mauser\">{{cite web|title=The 9.3x62mm Mauser|url=http://thebiggamehuntingblog.com/2013/09/the-93x62mm-mauser-html/|website=thebiggamehuntingblog.com|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn [[England]], [[Kynoch]] the well-known cartridge manufacturer, produced ammunition, referring to the 9.3\u00d762mm as '9.3mm Mauser'. Typically it was loaded as 'Metal Covered Soft Nose Bullet', {{convert|18.5|g|gr}} with the base marked simply Kynoch 9.3&nbsp;mm. This is no longer listed by them.\n\n==Elsewhere==\n{{More citations needed section|date=March 2020}}\nIn several [[European countries]], the 9.3x62mm remains a popular cartridge for hunting game like moose and wild boar, and it is offered as a standard chambering in rifles from most makers there. The [[CZ-USA]] [[CZ 550]] rifle in 9.3x62mm chambering became available in [[North America]] in 2002, and both rifle and cartridge are gaining a strong following there, as the cartridge has a slight power edge over the popular [[.35 Whelen]] cartridge. In [[US]], several ammunition makers including [[Federal Premium Ammunition|Federal]], [[Hornady]], [[Nosler]], and Swift offer factory-loaded 9.3x62mm sporting ammunition. Since surplus Scandinavian and European Mausers were been brought to Canada in 9.3 calibre in the early 1950s, Canadian hunters have used the 9.3\u00d762mm cartridge to hunt large game in [[Canada]] including [[bison]], all the deer species, and large bears. In recent years, [[\u010cesk\u00e1 Zbrojovka firearms|CZ]] of [[Czech Republic]], as well as [[SAKO]] and Tikka of [[Finland]] have imported many 9.3x62mm rifles to [[Canada]] and [[US]] where demand continues to be high.\n\n==Adequacy==\nThe 9.3\u00d762mm is considered ideal for hunting the larger and tougher African game species, such as [[lion]]s, [[leopard]]s, [[gemsbok]]s, [[Common eland|eland]]s, and [[wildebeest]]s. Most hunters consider it a viable all-around cartridge comparable to [[.338 Winchester Magnum]], [[9.3\u00d764mm Brenneke]], and [[.375 H&H Magnum]]. The 9.3\u00d762mm has taken cleanly every dangerous game species in [[Africa]].  Though it is of smaller bore than the legal minimum .375 calibre for dangerous game in most countries, many countries specifically make an exception for the 9.3\u00d762mm.<ref>[http://www.huntinginafrica.co.za/more-info/minimum-required-caliber/ Minimum required caliber for hunting Africa]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.farrenglobaladventures.com/Caliber%20Minimums.htm |title=Minimum Calibers for Africa |access-date=10 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714021703/http://www.farrenglobaladventures.com/Caliber%20Minimums.htm |archive-date=14 July 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>[http://www.napha-namibia.com/legal-information/hunting-laws-rifle-importation/ Hunting Laws & Rifle Importation NAPHA Namibia Professional Hunting Association]</ref> The 9.3\u00d762mm is considered adequate for European and North American game animals that may become dangerous, such as feral hogs and [[bear]]s. \n\n[[Sambar (deer)|Sambar]] hunters in [[Australia]] are turning to the 9.3\u00d762mm due to Federal Government's 1996 ban on self-loading rifles. {{cn|date=March 2012}} Thousands of deer hunters at once needed bolt-action rifles which delivered one-shot knockdown power on [[Sambar (deer)|Sambar]], and the 9.3\u00d762mm calibre has proven to be well up to that task.\n\n==See also==\n* [[9 mm caliber]]\n* [[9.3\u00d774mmR]]\n* [[9.3\u00d764mm Brenneke]]\n* [[List of rifle cartridges]]\n* [[Table of handgun and rifle cartridges]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{Cite web\n |url=http://www.reloadersnest.com/article_9362_oct2803.asp \n |title=The 9,3 x 62 mm Mauser is making a strong come back! \n |publisher=reloaders \n |accessdate=24 February 2006 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207003649/http://www.reloadersnest.com/article_9362_oct2803.asp \n |archivedate=7 Feb