 class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1983\n|''[[Knight Rider (1982 TV series)|Knight Rider]]''\n|Grace Fallon\n|Episode: \"K.I.T.T. the Cat\"\n|-\n|1983\u20131984\n|''[[Buffalo Bill (TV series)|Buffalo Bill]]''\n|Wendy Killian\n|26 episodes \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1984\n|''[[Fantasy Island]]''\n|Patricia Grayson\n|Episode: \"Don Juan's Lost Affair\"\n|-\n|''[[Riptide (U.S. TV series)|Riptide]]''\n|Dr. Melba Bozinsky\n|Episode: \"Raiders of the Lost Sub\"\n|-\n|1984\u20131986\n|''[[Family Ties]]''\n|Karen Nicholson \n|3 episodes \n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |1985\n|''Secret Weapons''\n|Tamara Reshevsky / Brenda\n|Television movie\n|-\n|''[[Remington Steele]]''\n|Sandy Dalrymple\n|Episode: \"Steele in the Chips\"\n|-\n|''[[Sara (1985 TV series)|Sara]]''\n|Sara McKenna\n|13 episodes \n|-\n|1989\n|''Trying Times''\n|Daphne\n|Episode: \"The Hit List\"\n|-\n|1990\n|''[[The Earth Day Special]]''\n|Kim\n|Television special\n|-\n|2000\u20132001\n|''[[The Geena Davis Show]]''\n|Teddie Cochran\n|22 episodes \n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Will & Grace]]''\n|Janet Adler\n|Episode: \"The Accidental Tsuris\"\n|-\n|2005\u20132006\n|''[[Commander in Chief (TV series)|Commander in Chief]]''\n|President Mackenzie Allen\n|18 episodes \n|-\n|2009\n|''Exit 19''\n|Gloria Woods\n|Television movie\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Coma (U.S. miniseries)|Coma]]''\n|Dr. Agnetta Lindquist\n|2-episode miniseries \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2013\n|''Untitled Bounty Hunter Project''\n|Mackenzie Ryan\n|Unsold TV pilot\n|-\n|''[[Doc McStuffins]]''\n|Princess Persephone (voice)\n|Episode: \"Sir Kirby and the Plucky Princess\"\n|-\n|2014\u20132018\n|''[[Grey's Anatomy]]''\n|Dr. Nicole Herman\n|13 episodes \n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Annedroids]]''\n|Student\n|Episode: \"Undercover Pigeon\"\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[The Exorcist (TV series)|The Exorcist]]''\n|[[Regan MacNeil|Angela Rance]]\n|10 episodes \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2019\n|''[[She-Ra and the Princesses of Power]]''\n|Huntara (voice)\n|3 episodes\n|-\n|''[[GLOW (TV series)|GLOW]]''\n|Sandy Devereaux St. Clair\n|6 episodes\n|}\n\n===Music videos===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Song\n! Artist\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1986\n| \"[[The Ultimate Collection (Bryan Ferry and Roxy Music album)|Help Me]]\"\n| [[Bryan Ferry]]\n| Footage from ''{{sortname|The|Fly|The Fly (1986 film)}}''\n|-\n| 1991\n| \"Part of Me, Part of You\"\n| [[Glenn Frey]]\n| Footage from ''[[Thelma & Louise]]''\n|-\n| 1992\n| \"[[This Used to Be My Playground]]\"\n| [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Footage from ''{{sortname|A|League of Their Own}}''\n|-\n| 1992\n| \"[[Now and Forever (Carole King song)|Now and Forever]]\"\n| [[Carole King]]\n|-\n| 1996\n| \"F.N.T.\"\n| [[Semisonic]]\n| Footage from ''[[The Long Kiss Goodnight]]''\n|-\n| 1999\n| \"You're Where I Belong\"\n| [[Trisha Yearwood]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Footage from ''[[Stuart Little (film)|Stuart Little]]''\n|-\n| 1999\n| \"I Need to Know\"\n| R Angels\n|-\n| 2002\n| \"[[I'm Alive (Celine Dion song)|I'm Alive]]\"\n| [[Celine Dion]]\n| Footage from ''[[Stuart Little 2]]''\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Association\n! Category\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n|-\n| 1987\n| [[Saturn Awards]]\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n| ''[[The Fly (1986 film)|The Fly]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 1989\n| [[Academy Awards]]\n| [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]]\n| ''[[The Accidental Tourist (film)|The Accidental Tourist]]''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 1991\n| [[Boston Society of Film Critics Awards]]\n| [[Boston Society of Film Critics Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n|rowspan=10| ''[[Thelma & Louise]]''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Los Angeles Film Critics Association Awards]]\n| [[Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[National Board of Review]]\n| [[National Board of Review Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] <small>(with [[Susan Sarandon]])</small>'\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[New York Film Critics Circle Awards]]\n| [[New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] <small>(with [[Susan Sarandon]])</small>\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\" | 1992\n| [[Academy Awards]]\n| [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Awards]]\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role|Best Actress in a Leading Role]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Chicago Film Critics Association Awards]]\n| [[Chicago Film Critics Association Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Globe Awards]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Drama|Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Drama]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[MTV Movie Awards]]\n| [[MTV Movie Awards|Best Female Performance]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[MTV Movie Awards]]\n| [[MTV Movie Awards|Best On-Screen Duo]] <small>(with [[Susan Sarandon]])</small>\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[People's Choice Awards]]\n| [[People's Choice Awards|Favorite Dramatic Motion Picture Actress]]\n| {{n/a}}\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1993\n| [[Golden Globe Awards]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| ''[[A League of Their Own]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[MTV Movie Awards]]\n| [[MTV Movie Awards|Best Female Performance]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 1995\n| [[Golden Globe Awards]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy]]\n| ''[[Speechless (1994 film)|Speechless]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 1997\n| [[Saturn Awards]]\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n| ''[[The Long Kiss Goodnight]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2000\n| [[Saturn Awards]]\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]]\n| ''[[Stuart Little (film)|Stuart Little]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2005\n| [[Satellite Awards]]\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Drama|Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Drama]]\n| rowspan=\"4\"| ''[[Commander in Chief (TV series)|Commander in Chief]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2006\n| [[Golden Globe Awards]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Drama|Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Drama]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmy Awards]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Screen Actors Guild Awards]]\n| [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Drama Series]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|2015\n|[[San Diego International Film Festival|San Diego Film Festival]]\n|[[List of San Diego International Film Festival award winners#SDFF2015 2|Reframed Humanitarian Award]]\n|Life's Work\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 2017\n| [[Fangoria]] Chainsaw Awards\n| Best TV Actress\n| ''[[The Exorcist (TV series)|The Exorcist]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2019\n| [[Academy Awards]]\n| [[Jean Hersholt Humanitarian Award]]\n| {{n/a}}\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Geena Davis}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb name|133|Geena Davis}}\n* {{Tcmdb name|45190|Geena Davis}}\n* {{Amg name|17342|Geena Davis}}\n* [http://www.thegeenadavisinstitute.org/ Geena Davis Institute on Gender in Media]\n* {{C-SPAN|geenadavis}}\n* {{Worldcat id|lccn-no94-21068}}\n* {{NYTtopic|people/d/geena_davis}}\n* [https://www.makers.com/geena-davis Geena Davis] Video produced by ''[[Makers: Women Who Make America]]''\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Geena Davis\n|list =\n{{AcademyAwardBestSupportingActress 1981-2000}}\n{{Boston Society of Film Critics Award for Best Actress}}\n{{David di Donatello for Best Foreign Actress}}\n{{GoldenGlobeBestActressTVDrama 2000-2019}}\n{{Jean Hersholt Humanitarian Award}}\n{{National Board of Review Award for Best Actress}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davis, Geena}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:American activists]]\n[[Category:American female archers]]\n[[Category:American Congregationalists]]\n[[Category:Female models from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:American feminists]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Best Drama Actress Golden Globe (television) winners]]\n[[Category:Best Supporting Actress Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Boston University College of Fine Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:David di Donatello winners]]\n[[Category:Feminist artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mensans]]\n[[Category:New England College alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Wareham, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:American women film producers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Geena Davis\n| image              = Geena Davis 2013 (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Davis at a NYC event in 2013\n| birth_name         = Virginia Elizabeth Davis\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1956|1|21}}\n| birth_place        = [[Wareham, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| alma_mater         = [[Boston University]] ([[Bachelor of Fine Arts|BFA]])\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Actress|producer|writer|athlete|model}}\n| years_active       = 1978\u2013present\n| height             = {{height|ft=6}}<ref name=\"oprah\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oprah.com/omagazine/Oprah-Interviews-Geena-Davis|title=Oprah Interviews Geena Davis|work=[[O, The Oprah Magazine|O]]|publisher=[[Hearst Corporation]]|last=Winfrey|first=Oprah|authorlink=Oprah Winfrey|date=December 2006|accessdate=October 5, 2015}}</ref>\n| spouse             = {{unbulleted list|{{marriage|Richard Emmolo|1982|1983|end=divorced}}|{{marriage|[[Jeff Goldblum]]|1987|1990|end=divorced}}|{{marriage|[[Renny Harlin]]|1993|1998|end=divorced}}}}\n| partner            = Reza Jarrahy (2001\u20132017)<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite magazine|url=https://people.com/movies/geena-davis-never-legally-married/|title=Geena Davis Says She Was Never Legally Married|magazine=People.com|author=Zauzmer, Emily|date=September 5, 2018|accessdate=September 6, 2018}}</ref>\n| children           = 3\n}}\n\n'''Virginia Elizabeth''' \"'''Geena'''\" '''Davis''' (born January 21, 1956)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VK0vR4fsaigC|title=The New Penguin Dictionary of Modern Quotations|first=Robert|last=Andrews|date=October 30, 2003|publisher=Penguin UK|accessdate=March 15, 2017|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sR4Ch1dMe8IC|title=The International Who's Who 2004|first=Europa|last=Publications|date=January 1, 2003|publisher=Psychology Press|accessdate=March 15, 2017|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribute.ca/people/geena-davis/2314/|title=Geena Davis biography and filmography - Geena Davis movies|publisher=|accessdate=March 15, 2017}}</ref> is an American actress and activist.<ref name=\"sportsillustrated.cnn.com\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/08/06/sports/olympics-geena-davis-zeros-in-with-bow-and-arrows.html | work=NY Times | title=OLYMPICS; Geena Davis Zeros In With Bow and Arrows| date= 6 August 1999 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150612123043/http://www.nytimes.com/1999/08/06/sports/olympics-geena-davis-zeros-in-with-bow-and-arrows.html|archivedate=June 12, 2015 |url-status=dead |accessdate=December 24, 2015}}</ref> Davis has received numerous accolades for her acting work in both film and television, and is noted for her portrayals of strong and authentic female characters as well as her involvement in advocacy for women in the industry.\n\nHaving graduated with a [[bachelor's degree]] in drama from [[Boston University]] in 1979, Davis signed with New York's [[Zoli modeling agency]] and started her career as a model. She made her acting debut in the film ''[[Tootsie]]'' (1982), in 1986 she starred in the thriller ''[[The Fly (1986 film)|The Fly]]'' (1986), which proved to be one of her first box office hits. While the fantasy comedy ''[[Beetlejuice]]'' (1988) brought her to international prominence, the drama ''[[The Accidental Tourist (film)|The Accidental Tourist]]'' (also 1988) earned her the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress]]. That same year, she also starred in ''[[Earth Girls are Easy]]'', which was not a box office success.  She cemented her leading actress status with her performance in the road film ''[[Thelma & Louise]]'' (1991), receiving a nomination for the [[Academy Award for Best Actress]]. Later she starred in '' [[A League of Their Own]]'' (1992), which proved to be a critical and box office success, earning her a Golden Globe Award nomination. Davis's roles in the box office failures ''[[Cutthroat Island]]'' (1995) and ''[[The Long Kiss Goodnight]]'' (1996), both directed by then-husband [[Renny Harlin]], were followed by a lengthy break and downturn in her career.\n\nDavis starred as the adoptive mother of the titular character in the [[Stuart Little (film)|''Stuart Little'' franchise]] (1999\u20132005) and as the first female president of the United States in the television series ''[[Commander in Chief (TV series)|Commander in Chief]]'' (2005\u20132006), winning the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Drama]] for her role in the latter. Her later films include ''[[Accidents Happen]]'' (2009) and ''[[Marjorie Prime]]'' (2017). She has portrayed the recurring role of Dr. Nicole Herman in ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]'' (2014\u20132015, 2018), and also starred as [[Regan MacNeil]]/Angela Rance in the first season of the horror television series ''[[The Exorcist (TV series)|The Exorcist]]'' (2017).\n\nIn 2004, Davis launched the [[Geena Davis Institute on Gender in Media]], which works collaboratively with the entertainment industry to dramatically increase the presence of female characters in media. Through the organization, she launched the annual [[Bentonville Film Festival]] in 2015, and executive produced the documentary ''[[This Changes Everything (2018 film)|This Changes Everything]]'' in 2018.\n\nIn 2019, in recognition of her work for gender equality, Davis received the [[Jean Hersholt Humanitarian Award]] from the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oscars.org/news/academy-honor-geena-davis-david-lynch-wes-studi-and-lina-wertmuller-2019-governors-awards|title=The Academy To Honor Geena Davis, David Lunch, Wes Studi and Lina Wertm\u00fcller at 2019 Governors Awards|date=2019-06-03|work=AMPAS|access-date=2019-06-04}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nDavis was born January 21, 1956, in [[Wareham, Massachusetts]]. Her mother, Lucille ({{nee|Cook}}; June 19, 1919 \u2013 November 15, 2001), was a teacher's assistant, and her father, William F. Davis (November 7, 1913 \u2013 April 2, 2009), was a civil engineer and church deacon; her parents were both from small towns in [[Vermont]].<ref>[http://www.southcoasttoday.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20090405/NEWS03/904050333/-1/rss37 \"Editor's notes: Fish out of water\"] April 8, 2009, South Coast Today</ref> She has an older brother named Danforth (\"Dan\").<ref>[http://www.filmreference.com/film/15/Geena-Davis.html ''Geena Davis biography'']. Film Reference.com</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Editor's notes: Fish out of water |url=http://www.wickedlocal.com/marion/news/lifestyle/columnists/x549600134/Editors-notes-Fish-out-of-water |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120716082405/http://www.wickedlocal.com/marion/news/lifestyle/columnists/x549600134/Editors-notes-Fish-out-of-water |archivedate=July 16, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nAt an early age, she became interested in music. She learned piano and [[flute]] and played [[organ (music)|organ]] well enough as a teenager to serve as an organist at her [[Congregational church|Congregationalist]] church in Wareham.<ref name=\"tca\">Stated on ''[[Inside the Actors Studio]]'', 2000</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Trends in Photography|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1989-07-14/news/vw-3598_1_geena-davis|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=July 14, 1989}}</ref> Davis attended [[Wareham High School]] and was an exchange student in [[Sandviken]], [[Sweden]], becoming fluent in [[Swedish language|Swedish]].<ref name=\"tca\" /> She attended [[New England College]] before earning a [[bachelor's degree]] in drama from [[Boston University]] in 1979.<ref name=\"tca\" /><ref name=\"NEC\">[http://www.nec.edu/new-england-college-receive-3-million-gift/ \"New England College to Receive $3 Million Gift\"], New England College news office</ref><ref name=\"HR122014\">{{cite magazine |last1=Sandberg |first1=Bryn Elise |title=Boston U: Hollywood's Secret Female Training Ground |magazine=The Hollywood Reporter |date=December 2014 |page=34 |url=http://www.bu.edu/cas/files/2015/01/THR_WIE_BUAlumni_44A.pdf |via=Boston University College of Arts and Sciences website |accessdate=17 August 2019}}</ref> Following her education, Davis served as a window [[mannequin]] for [[Ann Taylor (clothing retailer)|Ann Taylor]] until signing with New York's [[Zoli modeling agency]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800012507/bio |title=Davis bio at Yahoo Movies |publisher=Movies.yahoo.com |date= |accessdate=August 21, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604005517/http://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800012507/bio |archivedate=June 4, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Beginnings (1982\u20131987)===\nDavis was working as a model when she was cast by director [[Sydney Pollack]] in his film ''[[Tootsie]]'' (1982) as a soap opera actress whom she described as \"someone who's going to be in their underwear a lot of time\".<ref name=tca/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2016/feb/29/geena-davis-tv-girl-gender-equality-thelma-louise-women|title=Geena Davis: \u2018The more TV a girl watches, the fewer options she thinks she has in life\u2019|first=Homa|last=Khaleeli|date=February 29, 2016|publisher=|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> The film was the second most profitable screen production of 1982,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=main&id=tootsie.htm&adjust_yr=1&p=.htm|title=Tootsie (1982) - Box Office Mojo|website=www.boxofficemojo.com}}</ref> received ten [[Academy Awards]] nominations <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1983 |title=The 55th Academy Awards (1983) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=2011-10-09|publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences}}</ref> and is considered a [[cult classic]].<ref>{{cite web |title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Movies (10th Anniversary Edition) |url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/100Movies.pdf |publisher=[[American Film Institute]] |accessdate=2016-07-16 }}</ref> She next obtained the regular part of Wendy Killian in the television series ''[[Buffalo Bill (TV series)|Buffalo Bill]]'',<ref name=\"Buffalo\">{{IMDb title|84992|Buffalo Bill}}</ref> which aired from June 1983 to March 1984; she also had a writing credit in one episode.<ref name=\"Buffalo\"/> Despite the series' eleven [[Emmy Awards]] nominations, the lukewarm ratings led to its cancellation after two seasons. At the time, Davis guest-starred in ''[[Knight Rider (1982 TV series)|Knight Rider]]'', ''[[Riptide (U.S. TV series)|Riptide]]'', ''[[Family Ties]]'' and ''[[Remington Steele]]'', and followed with a series of her own, ''[[Sara (1985 TV series)|Sara]]'', which lasted 13 episodes. \nDuring this period, she landed an audition for the 1984 science fiction/action film [[The Terminator]] reading for the lead role of [[Sarah Connor (Terminator)|Sarah Connor]], a part which eventually went to [[Linda Hamilton]]. In ''[[Fletch (film)|Fletch]]'' (1985), an action comedy, Davis appeared as the colleague of a ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' undercover reporter trying to expose drug trafficking on the beaches of Los Angeles, opposite [[Chevy Chase]].<ref>{{cite web\n | title = Fletch\n | website = [[Box Office Mojo]]\n | url = https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=fletch.htm\n | accessdate = 2009-02-10\n}}</ref> In 1985, she also starred in the horror comedy ''[[Transylvania 6-5000 (1985 film)|Transylvania 6-5000]]'', as a nymphomaniac vampire alongside future husband [[Jeff Goldblum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=transylvania6-5000.htm|title=Transylvania 6-5000|publisher=boxofficemojo.com|access-date=2011-04-08}}</ref> They would reunite professionally in the sci-fi thriller ''[[The Fly (1986 film)|The Fly]]'' (1986), loosely based on [[George Langelaan]]'s 1957 [[The Fly (George Langelaan)|short story of the same name]] and in which Davis portrayed a science journalist and the love interest of an eccentric scientist. Caryn James, of ''[[The New York Times]]'', found her to be \"stiff\" in ''The Fly'', a film she considered \"intense, all right, but not scary or sad, or even intentionally funny\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/08/15/movies/film-the-fly-with-jeff-goldblum.html|title=Film: 'The Fly,' with Jeff Goldblum|first=Caryn|last=James|date=August 15, 1986|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> Nevertheless, it was a commercial success and helped to establish her as an actress.<ref>Aubrey Solomon, ''Twentieth Century Fox: A Corporate and Financial History'', Scarecrow Press, 1989 p260</ref> In 1987 she appeared with Goldblum again in the offbeat comedy ''[[Earth Girls Are Easy]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/1987/film/reviews/earth-girls-are-easy-1200427598/|title=Earth Girls Are Easy|last=|first=|date=|website=Variety|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Recognition and critical acclaim (1988\u20131993)===\n[[File:Geena Davis (1989) crop.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Davis at the [[61st Academy Awards]] in 1989]]\nDirector [[Tim Burton]] cast Davis in his film ''[[Beetlejuice]]'' (1988),<ref name=bob>{{cite book | last=Salisbury | first=Mark | title=Burton on Burton: Revised Edition | isbn=0-571-20507-0 | publisher=[[Faber and Faber]] |year=2000}}</ref> as one half of a recently deceased young couple who become ghosts haunting their former house, alongside [[Alec Baldwin]], [[Michael Keaton]] and [[Winona Ryder]]. The film made $73.7 million from a budget of $15 million, and Davis's performance and the overall film received mostly positive reviews from critics.<ref>''Beetlejuice'' at [https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/beetlejuice/ Rotten Tomatoes.com]; accessed on May 5, 2007.</ref>\n\nDavis took on the role of an animal hospital employee and dog trainer with a sickly son in the drama ''[[The Accidental Tourist (film)|The Accidental Tourist]]'' (1988), opposite [[William Hurt]] and [[Kathleen Turner]]. Critic [[Roger Ebert]], who gave the film four stars out of four, wrote: \"Davis, as Muriel, brings an unforced wackiness to her role in scenes like the one where she belts out a song while she's doing the dishes. But she is not as simple as she sometimes seems [...]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-accidental-tourist-1989|title=The Accidental Tourist Movie Review (1989) - Roger Ebert|first=Roger|last=Ebert|website=www.rogerebert.com}}</ref> The film was a critical and commercial success, and she received an [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] as [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]] for her appearance in it. She would work again with Jeff Goldblum in the sci-fi film ''[[Earth Girls Are Easy]]'' (also 1988), in which she was cast as a [[valley girl]] and manicurist.\n\nDavis appeared as the girlfriend of a man who, dressed as a clown, robs a bank in midtown Manhattan, in the comedy ''[[Quick Change]]'' (1990), based on a book of the same name by [[Jay Cronley]], and a remake of the 1985 French film ''[[Hold-Up (1985 film)|Hold-Up]]'' starring [[Jean-Paul Belmondo]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0100449/movieconnections |title=Quick Change (1990): Connections |website=IMDb |accessdate=January 28, 2018}}</ref> Despite modest box office returns for the film,<ref name=\"rottentomatoes\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/quick_change/ |title=Quick Change |date=July 13, 1990 |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=December 8, 2014}}</ref> the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' found the lead actors to be \"funny and creative while keeping their characters life-size\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagoreader.com/chicago/quick-change/Film?oid=1054868|title=Quick Change|first=Jonathan|last=Rosenbaum|website=Chicago Reader}}</ref> Davis next starred with [[Susan Sarandon]] in [[Ridley Scott]]'s road film ''[[Thelma & Louise]]'' (1991), playing friends who embark on a road trip with unforeseen consequences. A critical and commercial success, the film is considered a classic, as it influenced other films and artistic works and became a landmark [[feminist film]]. She received an [[Academy Award]] nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] for her role.<ref name=tca/> The film also featured Brad Pitt in his breakout role as a drifter, and in his 2020 acceptance speech for Best Supporting Actor, he thanked director Ridley Scott and Geena Davis for \"giving me my first shot.\" https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/oscars-read-brad-pitts-acceptance-speech-best-supporting-actor-1277805  \n\nIn 1992, Davis starred alongside [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] and [[Tom Hanks]] in ''[[A League of Their Own]]'' as a baseball player on an all-women's team. It reached [[List of 1992 box office number-one films in the United States|number one on the box-office]], became the tenth highest-grossing film of the year in North America,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=leagueoftheirown.htm|title=A League of Their Own|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=April 11, 2014}}</ref> and earned her a Best Actress [[Golden Globe Award]] nomination.<ref>{{cite news|last=Joe Brown|date=July 3, 1992|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/aleagueoftheirownpgbrown_a0ade7.htm|work=Washington Post|title='A League of Their Own' (PG)|accessdate=December 24, 2015}}</ref> She played a television reporter in the comedy ''[[Hero (1992 film)|Hero]]'' (also 1992), alongside [[Dustin Hoffman]] and [[Andy Garcia]]. While the film flopped at the box office, Roger Ebert felt that Davis was \"bright and convincing as the reporter (her best line, after surviving the plane crash, is shouted through an ambulance door: \"This is my story! I did the research!\")\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/hero-1992|title=Hero Movie Review & Film Summary (1992) - Roger Ebert|first=Roger|last=Ebert|website=www.rogerebert.com}}</ref>\n\n===Action roles, voice work, hiatus, sitcom and other television roles (1997\u20132009)===\nIn 1994's ''[[Angie (1994 film)|Angie]]'', Davis played an office worker who lives in the [[Bensonhurst]] section of [[Brooklyn]] and dreams of a better life. The film received mixed reviews from critics, who felt she could have been better in this movie or another set in Brooklyn,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/angie|title=Angie (1994)|publisher=|via=www.rottentomatoes.com}}</ref> and was a commercial failure. In her other 1994 release, ''[[Speechless (1994 film)|Speechless]]'', Davis reunited with Michael Keaton to play insomniac writers who fall in love until they realize that both are writing speeches for rival candidates in a [[New Mexico]] election. Despite negative reviews and modest box office returns, she was nominated for a [[Golden Globe Award]] for Best Actress \u2013 Musical or Comedy for her performance.[[File:Gina Davis 2004.jpg|thumb|upright|Davis in 2004]]\nDavis teamed up with her then-husband, director [[Renny Harlin]], for the films ''[[Cutthroat Island]]'' (1995) and ''[[The Long Kiss Goodnight]]'' (1996), with Harlin hoping that they would turn her into an action star. While ''The Long Kiss Goodnight'' managed to become a moderate success, ''Cutthroat Island'' flopped critically and commercially and was once listed as having the \"largest box office loss\" by ''[[Guinness World Records]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/content_pages/record.asp?recordid=50762|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051127180839/http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/content_pages/record.asp?recordid=50762|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 27, 2005|title=Arts and Media/Movies/Big Box Office Loss|date=November 27, 2005}}</ref> The film is credited to be a contributing factor in the demise of Davis as a [[bankable star]]. She divorced Harlin in 1998 and took an \"unusually long\" two years off to reflect on her career, according to ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/12/20/movies/film-geena-davis-is-back-weaklings-step-aside.html|title=FILM; Geena Davis Is Back. Weaklings Step Aside.|first=James|last=Sterngold|date=December 20, 1998|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> She appeared as Eleanor Little in the well-received family comedy ''[[Stuart Little (film)|Stuart Little]]'' (1999), a role she reprised in ''[[Stuart Little 2]]'' (2002) and again in ''[[Stuart Little 3: Call of the Wild]]'' (2005).<ref>{{IMDb title|164912|section=awards|Stuart Little}}</ref>\n\nBy the mid and late 1990s, Davis's film career had become less noteworthy and critical acclaim had waned. In a 2016 interview with ''Vulture'', she recalled: \"Film roles really did start to dry up when I got into my 40s.\u00a0If you look at [[IMDb]], up until that age, I made roughly one film a year. In my entire 40s, I made one movie, ''Stuart Little''. I was getting offers, but for nothing meaty or interesting like in my 30s. I'd been completely ruined and spoiled. I mean, I got to play a pirate captain! I got to do every type of role, even if the movie failed.\"<ref name=\"vi\">https://www.vulture.com/2016/05/geena-davis-on-fighting-for-more-roles-for-women.html</ref>\n\nDavis starred in the sitcom ''[[The Geena Davis Show]]'', which aired for one season on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] during the [[2000\u201301 United States network television schedule|2000\u201301 U.S. television season]].<ref>{{cite news|title= A Star Vehicle Sputters: CBS Cancels 'Bette'|newspaper= [[The New York Times]]|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2001/03/07/arts/a-star-vehicle-sputters-cbs-cancels-bette.html|accessdate=June 10, 2012}}</ref> She went on to star in the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] television series ''[[Commander in Chief (TV series)|Commander in Chief]]'', portraying the first female president of the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/19851|title=Geena Davis Would Love to Be Part of a 'Beetlejuice' Sequel|publisher=BloodyDisgusting}}</ref> While this role garnered her a Golden Globe for Best Actress in a Drama Series in 2006, the series was cancelled after its first season; Davis admitted she was \"devastated\" by its cancellation in a 2016 interview. \"I still haven't gotten over it. I really wanted it to work. It was on Tuesday nights opposite ''[[House (TV series)|House]]'', which wasn't ideal. But we were the best new show that fall. Then, in January, we were opposite ''[[American Idol]]''. They said, 'The ratings are going to suffer, so we should take you off the air for the entire run of ''Idol'', and bring it back in May. I put a lot of time and effort into getting it on another network, too, but it didn't work\".<ref name=\"vi\" /> She was also nominated for an [[Emmy Award]] and a [[Screen Actors Guild|SAG]] Award for Outstanding Female Actor in a Drama Series. She was awarded the 2006 [[Women in Film Los Angeles|Women in Film]] [[Women in Film Crystal + Lucy Awards#THE LUCY AWARD|Lucy Award]].<ref>[http://wif.org/past-recipients Lucy Award, past recipients]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724120329/http://www.wif.org/past-recipients |date=July 24, 2011 }} WIF web site</ref>\n\nDavis was the only American actor to be cast in the Australian-produced film ''[[Accidents Happen]]'' (2009), portraying a foul-mouthed and strict mother. She stated that it was the most fun she had ever had on a film set, and felt a deep friendship and connection to both of the actors who played her sons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popentertainment.com/geenadavis.htm|title=PopEntertainment.com: Geena Davis interview about 'Accidents Happen.'|website=www.popentertainment.com}}</ref> Written by [[Brian Carbee]] and based on his own childhood and adolescence, the film received a limited theatrical release and mixed reviews from critics. ''Variety'' found it to be \"led by a valiant Geena Davis\", despite a \"script that mistakes abuse for wit\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2010/film/reviews/accidents-happen-1117942642/|title=Accidents Happen|first1=Russell|last1=Edwards|first2=Russell|last2=Edwards|date=April 28, 2010|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Professional expansion (2010s)===\nFollowing a long period of intermittent workload, Davis often ventured into television acting, and through her organization, the [[Geena Davis Institute on Gender in Media]], saw her career expanded during the 2010s. In 2012, Davis starred as a psychiatrist in the miniseries ''[[Coma (U.S. miniseries)|Coma]]'',  based on the 1977 novel ''[[Coma (novel)|Coma]]'' by [[Robin Cook (American novelist)|Robin Cook]] and the subsequent [[Coma (1978 film)|1978 film]]. She played a powerful female movie executive in the critically acclaimed comedy ''[[In a World...]]'' (2013), the directorial debut of [[Lake Bell]].<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/aug/09/entertainment/la-et-mn-lake-bell-on-the-soapbox-moment-in-her-in-a-world-20130809|title=Lake Bell on the 'soapbox moment' in her 'In a World...'|first=Mark|last=Olsen|date=August 9, 2013|publisher=|via=LA Times}}</ref> Bell found Davis's only dialogue to be her favorite in the film and called it her \"soapbox moment\".<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nIn 2014, Davis provided her voice for the English version of the [[Studio Ghibli]] animated film ''[[When Marnie Was There]]'', as she was drawn to the film's abundant stories and strong use of female characters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/articles/87809-geena-davis-talks-when-marnie-was-there-studio-ghiblis-brilliant-use-of-female-characters|title=Geena Davis On Her New Film's Strong Female Roles|first=Allyson|last=Koerner|website=Bustle}}</ref> She played the recurring role of Dr. Nicole Herman, an attending fetal surgeon with a life-threatening brain tumor, during the 11th season of ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]'' (2014\u201315). In 2015, Davis launched an annual film festival to be held in [[Bentonville, Arkansas]], to highlight diversity in film, accepting films that prominently feature minorities and women in the cast and crew. The first [[Bentonville Film Festival]] took place from May 5\u20139, 2015.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/geena-davis-launching-bentonville-film-festival-to-push-for-diversity-in-film-1201393302/ |title=Geena Davis Launching Bentonville Film Festival to Push for Diversity in Film |magazine=Variety |accessdate=January 6, 2015}}</ref> Davis appeared as the mother of a semi-famous television star in the comedy ''[[Me Him Her]]'' (2016).\n\nIn the television series ''[[The Exorcist (TV series)|The Exorcist]]'' (2016), based on [[The Exorcist (film)|the 1973 film of the same name]], Davis took on the role of grown-up [[Regan MacNeil]], who has renamed herself Angela Rance to find peace and anonymity from her ordeal as a child. ''The Exorcist'' was a success with critics and audiences. In 2017, Davis starred in the film adaptation ''[[Marjorie Prime]]'', alongside [[Jon Hamm]], playing the daughter of an 85-year old experiencing the first symptoms of [[Alzheimer\u2019s disease]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Geena Davis on Playing Opposite Jon Hamm in MARJORIE PRIME, 'I'm Excited!'|date=October 11, 2015|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/Geena-Davis-on-Playing-Opposite-Jon-Hamm-in-MARJORIE-PRIME-Im-Excited-20151011|work=Broadway World|accessdate=December 24, 2015}}</ref> and appeared as the imaginary god of a heavyset 13-year-old girl in the comedy ''[[Don't Talk to Irene]]''. ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' felt that she \"shine[d]\" and stole \"every scene\" in ''Marjorie Prime'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/08/marjorie-prime-movie-review|title=Marjorie Prime Review: This Quiet Sci-Fi Is the Best Kind of Virtual Insanity|first=Jordan|last=Hoffman|website=HWD}}</ref> while ''Variety'', on her role in ''Don't Talk to Irene'', remarked: \"There\u2019s no arguing the preternatural coolness of Geena Davis \u2014a fact celebrated in self-conscious fashion by ''Don\u2019t Talk to Irene'', a familiar type of coming-of-age film whose most distinguishing feature is the presence of the actress\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/reviews/dont-talk-to-irene-review-1202711091/|title=Film Review: \u2018Don\u2019t Talk to Irene\u2019|first1=Nick|last1=Schager|first2=Nick|last2=Schager|date=February 27, 2018|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Davis returned to ''Grey's Anatomy'', reprising the role of Dr. Nicole Herman in the show's [[Grey's Anatomy (season 15)|15th season]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/04/greys-anatomy-geena-davis-returns-reprise-dr-nicole-herman-1202372822/|title=\u2018Grey\u2019s Anatomy\u2019: Geena Davis Returns To Reprise Dr. Herman Role|first1=Nellie Andreeva,Denise|last1=Petski|first2=Nellie|last2=Andreeva|first3=Denise|last3=Petski|date=April 20, 2018|publisher=}}</ref> and executive produced the documentary ''[[This Changes Everything (2018 film)|This Changes Everything]]'', in which she was also interviewed about her experiences in the industry. The film premiered at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]], where it was named first runner-up for the [[Toronto International Film Festival People's Choice Award: Documentaries|People's Choice Award: Documentaries]].<ref>[https://www.screendaily.com/news/green-book-boosts-awards-season-prospects-with-tiff-audience-award-win/5132687.article \"'Green Book' boosts awards season prospects with TIFF audience award win\"]. ''[[Screen Daily]]'', September 16, 2018.</ref> In 2019, she joined the voice cast of ''[[She-Ra and the Princesses of Power]]'' as Huntara.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/she-ra-the-princess-of-power-geena-davis-joins-netflix-series-as-huntara-1202612249/|title=\u2018She-Ra & The Princess Of Power\u2019: Geena Davis Joins Netflix Series as Huntara|last=Boucher|first=Geoff|magazine=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]]|date=May 10, 2019|accessdate=May 11, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190511033212/https://deadline.com/2019/05/she-ra-the-princess-of-power-geena-davis-joins-netflix-series-as-huntara-1202612249/|archivedate=May 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n===Marriages and family===\n[[File:Reza Jarrahy and Geena Davis at the 2009 Tribeca Film Festival.jpg|thumb|right|Reza Jarrahy and Davis in 2009]]\n\nDavis has been married four times.<ref name=\"people\">{{cite magazine|last=Silverman |first=Stephen M. |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,622517,00.html|title=Geena Davis a Bride for Fourth Time |magazine=People.com |date=September 5, 2001 |accessdate=August 21, 2011}}</ref> Previously to Richard Emmolo (1982\u20131983); actor [[Jeff Goldblum]] (1987\u20131990); and [[Renny Harlin]] (1993\u20131998).\n\nOn September 1, 2001, Davis married Reza Jarrahy (b. 1971).{{citation needed|date=June 2019}} They have three children: a daughter, Alizeh (born April 2002), and fraternal twin sons, Kaiis and Kian (born May 2004).<ref name=\"bare_url\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,623873,00.html | magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]] magazine |date=April 19, 2002 |accessdate=August 21, 2011 |title=Mothers Over the Age of 40: PEOPLE}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Blash |first=Margi |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20150200,00.html |title=Hollywood Baby Boom |magazine=People.com |date=May 31, 2004 |accessdate=August 21, 2011}}</ref> In May 2018, Jarrahy filed for divorce from Davis; listing their date of separation as November 15, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tmz.com/2018/05/08/geena-davis-divorce-husband/|title=Geena Davis' Husband Files For Divorce|publisher=TMZ.com|date=May 8, 2018|accessdate=August 26, 2018}}</ref> Davis responded by filing a petition in which she claimed that she and Jarrahy were never legally married.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===Activism===\n[[File:Geena Davis walks with Dr. John Gallin (26429787593).jpg|thumb|Geena Davis with Dr. John Gallin at the National Institute of Health to discuss the Geena Davis Institute on Gender in the Media.]]\nDavis is a supporter of the [[Women's Sports Foundation]] and an advocate for [[Title IX]], an [[Act of Congress]] focusing on equality in sports opportunities, now expanded to prohibit [[gender discrimination]] in United States' educational institutions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.teamusa.org/News/2012/February/18/Actor-Geena-Davis-targets-women-s-sports|title=Actor Geena Davis targets women-s sports|work=Team USA|access-date=2017-12-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.looktothestars.org/charity/womens-sports-foundation|title=Women's Sports Foundation: Celebrity Supporters|website=Look to the Stars|language=en|access-date=2017-12-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, while watching children's television programs and videos with her daughter, Davis noticed an imbalance in the ratio of male to female characters. Davis went on to sponsor the largest research project ever undertaken on gender in children's entertainment (resulting in four discrete studies, including one on children's television) at the [[USC Annenberg School for Communication and Journalism|Annenberg School for Communication]] at the [[University of Southern California]]. The study, directed by Stacy Smith, showed that there were nearly three males to every one female character in the nearly 400 G, PG, PG-13, and R-Rated movies the undergraduate team of Annenberg students analyzed.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Smith|first1=Stacy L.|last2=Choueiti|first2=Marc|last3=Pieper|first3=Katherine|last4=Gillig|first4=Traci|last5=Lee|first5=Carmen|last6=DeLuca|first6=Dylan|title=Inequality in 700 Popular Films: Examining Portrayals of Gender, Race,  & LGBT Status from 2007 to 2014|url=http://annenberg.usc.edu/pages/~/media/MDSCI/Inequality%20in%20700%20Popular%20Films%208215%20Final%20for%20Posting.ashx}}</ref> In 2005, Davis teamed up with the non-profit group, ''Dads and Daughters'', to launch a venture dedicated to balancing the number of male and female characters in children's television and movie programming.<ref>{{cite web|last=Burch |first=Ariel Z |title=Geena Davis: In a league of her own |url=http://www.wickedlocal.com/westford/news/x1817203582#axzz1xbUAZtIx |date=March 15, 2008 |accessdate=June 12, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130117033236/http://www.wickedlocal.com/westford/news/x1817203582 |archivedate=January 17, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nDavis launched the [[Geena Davis Institute on Gender in Media]] in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thegeenadavisinstitute.org/ |title=Geena Davis Institute on Gender in Media |publisher=Thegeenadavisinstitute.org |date= |accessdate=August 21, 2011}}</ref> The Institute's first focus is an on-the-ground program that works collaboratively with the entertainment industry to dramatically increase the presence of female characters in media aimed at children and to reduce stereotyping of females by the male-dominated industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.economist.com/news/books-and-arts/21737490-furore-hollywood-will-result-different-stories-making-it-screen|title=The aftermath of the Weinstein scandal|website=The Economist}}</ref> It seeks to address [[inequality in Hollywood]]. For her work in this field she received an honorary Doctor of Fine Arts degree from [[Bates College]] in May 2009<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bates.edu/x202708.xml |title=List of 2009 Bates honorands at Bates College web site |publisher=Bates.edu |date=April 9, 2009 |accessdate=August 21, 2011}}</ref> and the Academy's [[Jean Hersholt Humanitarian Award]], an Honorary Oscar, in 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oscars.org/news/academy-honor-geena-davis-david-lynch-wes-studi-and-lina-wertmuller-2019-governors-awards|title=The Academy To Honor Geena Davis, David Lunch, Wes Studi and Lina Wertm\u00fcller at 2019 Governors Awards|date=2019-06-03|work=AMPAS|access-date=2019-06-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Davis became one of a handful of celebrities attached to [[USAID]] and [[Ad Council]]'s [[USAID#East Africa|FWD]] campaign, an awareness initiative tied to that year's East Africa drought. She joined [[Uma Thurman]], [[Chanel Iman]] and [[Josh Hartnett]] in television and internet ads to \"forward the facts\" about the crisis.<ref>[http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/dr-jill-biden-joins-usaid-and-ad-council-to-debut-fwd-campaign-for-the-crisis-in-the-horn-of-africa-132605078.html \"Dr. Jill Biden Joins USAID and Ad Council to Debut FWD Campaign for the Crisis in the Horn of Africa\"]. [[PR Newswire]]. October 26, 2011.</ref>\n\n===Sports===\nIn July 1999, Davis was one of 300 women who vied for a semifinals berth in the U.S. Olympic [[archery]] team to participate in the Sydney [[2000 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"sportsillustrated.cnn.com\"/><ref name=tca/> She placed 24th and did not qualify for the team, but participated as a wild-card entry in the Sydney International Golden Arrow competition.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/more/archery/news/1999/09/21/davis_archery/ | work=CNN | title=Geena Davis still causing commotion in archery | date=September 21, 1999 | accessdate=May 3, 2010}}</ref> In August 1999 Davis stated that she was not an athlete growing up and that her introduction to archery was in 1997, two years before her tryouts.{{r|sportsillustrated.cnn.com}}\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title \n! Role \n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1982\n|''[[Tootsie]]''\n|April Page\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1985\n|''[[Fletch (film)|Fletch]]''\n|Larry\n|\n|-\n|''[[Transylvania 6-5000 (1985 film)|Transylvania 6-5000]]''\n|Odette\n|\n|-\n|1986\n|''{{sortname|The|Fly|The Fly (1986 film)}}''\n|Veronica \"Ronnie\" Quaife\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |1988\n|''[[Beetlejuice]]''\n|Barbara Maitland\n|\n|-\n|''[[Earth Girls Are Easy]]''\n|Valerie Gail\n|\n|-\n|''{{sortname|The|Accidental Tourist|The Accidental Tourist (film)}}''\n|Muriel Pritchett\n|Academy Award winner: Best Supporting Actress\n|-\n|1990\n|''[[Quick Change]]''\n|Phyllis Potter\n|\n|-\n|1991\n|''[[Thelma & Louise]]''\n|Thelma Dickinson\n|Academy Award nomination: Best Actress\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1992\n|''{{sortname|A|League of Their Own}}''\n|Dottie Hinson\n\n|\n|-\n|''[[Hero (1992 film)|Hero]]''\n|Gale Gayley\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1994\n|''[[Angie (1994 film)|Angie]]''\n|Angie Scacciapensieri\n|\n|-\n|''[[Speechless (1994 film)|Speechless]]''\n|Julia Mann\n|Producer\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Cutthroat Island]]''\n|Morgan Adams\n|\n|-\n|1996\n|''{{sortname|The|Long Kiss Goodnight}}''\n|Samantha Caine / Charlene \"Charly\" Baltimore\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Stuart Little (film)|Stuart Little]]''\n|rowspan=\"3\" |Mrs. Eleanor Little\n|\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[Stuart Little 2]]''\n|\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[Stuart Little 3: Call of the Wild]]''\n|Voice\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Accidents Happen]]''\n|Gloria Conway\n|\n|-\n|2013\n|''[[In a World...]]''\n|Katherine Huling\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[When Marnie Was There]]''\n|Yoriko Sasaki \n|Voice; English version\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Me Him Her]]''\n|Mrs. Ehrlick\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2017\n|''[[Marjorie Prime]]''\n|Tess\n|\n|-\n|''[[Don't Talk to Irene]]''\n|Herself\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[This Changes Everything (2018 film)|This Changes Everything]]''\n| Herself\n| Documentary; executive producer\n|-\n| TBA\n| ''[[Ava (upcoming film)|Ava]]''\n|\n| ''Post-production''\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title \n! Role \n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1983\n|''[[Knight Rider (1982 TV series)|Knight Rider]]''\n|Grace Fallon\n|Episode: \"K.I.T.T. the Cat\"\n|-\n|1983\u20131984\n|''[[Buffalo Bill (TV series)|Buffalo Bill]]''\n|Wendy Killian\n|26 episodes \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1984\n|''[[Fantasy Island]]''\n|Patricia Grayson\n|Episode: \"Don Juan's Lost Affair\"\n|-\n|''[[Riptide (U.S. TV series)|Riptide]]''\n|Dr. Melba Bozinsky\n|Episode: \"Raiders of the Lost Sub\"\n|-\n|1984\u20131986\n|''[[Family Ties]]''\n|Karen Nicholson \n|3 episodes \n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |1985\n|''Secret Weapons''\n|Tamara Reshevsky / Brenda\n|Television movie\n|-\n|''[[Remington Steele]]''\n|Sandy Dalrymple\n|Episode: \"Steele in the Chips\"\n|-\n|''[[Sara (1985 TV series)|Sara]]''\n|Sara McKenna\n|13 episodes \n|-\n|1989\n|''Trying Times''\n|Daphne\n|Episode: \"The Hit List\"\n|-\n|1990\n|''[[The Earth Day Special]]''\n|Kim\n|Television special\n|-\n|2000\u20132001\n|''[[The Geena Davis Show]]''\n|Teddie Cochran\n|22 episodes \n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Will & Grace]]''\n|Janet Adler\n|Episode: \"The Accidental Tsuris\"\n|-\n|2005\u20132006\n|''[[Commander in Chief (TV series)|Commander in Chief]]''\n|President Mackenzie Allen\n|18 episodes \n|-\n|2009\n